<p> <strong id="pp12s">Promotion Procedure - 1st &amp; 2nd Semesters</strong></p>
<p> At&nbsp;<strong>first and second semester promotion meetings</strong>, the promotion committee looks at the student's academic performance for the semester as an indicator of probable future success in the program. The student's academic record may also be considered in the context of written documentation which the co-ordinator would have received from the student. This documentation clarifies the circumstances that might explain lapses in a student¡¯s academic performance. (For example, lengthy hospitalization during the semester).At this level, academic performance and extenuating circumstances therefore become the criteria that guide the promotion committee in the application of the following policies:</p>
<p> Any grade of DNC, DNA, or F entered on a student transcript is viewed as "<strong>NOT SUCCESSFUL</strong>" in a subject by the promotion committee.<br /> &nbsp;<br /> 1. A student may be told to repeat the subject(s) for which the student received the F, DNC, or DNA grade(s) in the previous semester. A second unsuccessful attempt in a professional subject may result in the student being withdrawn from the full-time&nbsp; program.</p>
<p> 2. A student may be withdrawn from the full-time program for up to two semesters&nbsp;<strong>if not successful</strong>&nbsp;in two professional subjects. Re-admission to the program depends upon successful completion of designated courses in an alternate setting with the minimum required grade of "B" to be attained.</p>
<p> 3. A student may be withdrawn from the full-time program&nbsp;<strong>if not successful</strong>&nbsp;in three or more semester subjects. Students are advised to consult with their co-ordinator or a guidance counselor to investigate alternate career paths.</p>
<p> 4. A student may be put 'on probation' for the next semester and/or recommended for a reduced course load due to a low grade point average (semester GPA &lt;1.8). A student on probation is not being withdrawn; the student is being given the opportunity to improve academic performance. A student who fails to improve their academic performance while 'on probation' may be asked to withdraw from the program.</p>
<p> 5. Student transcripts are reviewed each semester.&nbsp; Upon successful completion of a subject that was previously graded DNC, DNA or F, the unsuccessful grade is moved to a section of the transcript called "Not Applicable to the Current Program".</p>
<p> 6. The President's Honours List is a designation granted to those students who meet ALL of the following conditions in an academic semester:</p>
<ul>
<li>GPA of 4.0 (grades of A or better in all credit courses and SAT grades for all non-credit courses)</li>
<li>Enrollment in first semester English or above (if part of the program)</li>
<li>A curriculum course load for the designated semester (for example, students affiliated to Semester 1 of CPD must be registered in six subjects; students in Semesters 2 through 6 of CPA must be registered for five subjects)</li>
</ul>
